properties.headline: Special Weather Statement issued February 12 at 4:43PM CST by NWS Green Bay WI
properties.description:
An arctic cold front across northern Wisconsin will drop southward
across the Fox Valley and lakeshore region early this evening. The
arctic front will be noted by a wind shift to the north or
northwest with sustained winds of 20 to 30 mph with gusts to 35
mph, and a sudden drop in air temperatures.

Light snow will overspread the Fox Valley and lakeshore region
early this evening with the arctic front and a system passing to
the south of the area. The snow should taper off late tonight.
Snowfall totals of 1 to 3 inches are expected by daybreak on
Thursday.

The combination of the falling snow, along with melting snow on
pavement surfaces and falling air temperatures well below freezing
could lead to a flash freeze by mid evening. Gusty northerly
winds may also create some areas of blowing and drifting snow.

Overnight, temperatures are expected to fall into the single
digits to around 10 above zero. The combination of the cold
temperatures and gusty northerly winds will produce wind chill
readings down to around 10 below zero late tonight into Thursday
morning. Wind chill readings this low can produce frost bite in 30
minutes.

Allow extra travel time if you will be driving this evening as
roads will become slippery due to ice or snow. If venturing
outdoors overnight, wear layers of clothing along with a hat and
gloves to protect yourself from the cold.

NWSheadline: HAZARDOUS TRAVEL CONDITIONS EXPECTED TO DEVELOP THIS EVENING FOLLOWED BY COLD WIND CHILLS OVERNIGHT
